04847nam a22006975i 9780520973190DE-B159720240306124542.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20192019cau    fo  d z      eng d  a2019012205  a97805209731907 a10.1525/97805209731902doi  a(DE-B1597)541510  a(OCoLC)1096233645  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA00aPN1995.9.C543bM37 2020 4aQ180.55.M4bH365 2019 7aHIS0350002bisacsh04a001.422231 aMarez, Curtis, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aUniversity Babylon :bFilm and Race Politics on Campus /cCurtis Marez. 1aBerkeley, CA : bUniversity of California Press, c[2019] 4cÂ©2019  a1 online resource (264 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aAmerican Crossroads ;v5700tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction: University Babylon, the Campus Tour -- t1. Indigenous Students and Students of Color in Silent Cinema -- t2. Race and Respectability in the University of California -- t3. Brown Universities, or the Question of Administration -- t4. Looking at Student Debt in Films by People of Color -- tAfterword: University Babylon Revisited -- tNotes -- tFilmography -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aFrom the silent era to the present, film productions have shaped the way the public views campus life. Collaborations between universities and Hollywood entities have disseminated influential ideas of race, gender, class, and sexual difference. Even more directly, Hollywood has drawn writers, actors, and other talent from ranks of professors and students while also promoting the industry in classrooms, curricula, and film studies programs. In addition to founding film schools, university administrators have offered campuses as filming locations. In University Babylon, Curtis Marez argues that cinema has been central to the uneven incorporation and exclusion of different kinds of students, professors, and knowledge. Working together, Marez argues, film and educational institutions have produced a powerful ideology that links respectability to academic merit in order to marginalize and manage people of color. Combining concepts and methods from critical university studies, ethnic studies, native studies, and film studies, University Babylon analyzes the symbolic and institutional collaborations between Hollywood filmmakers and university administrators over the representation of students and, by extension, college life more broadly.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aCollege life filmszUnited StatesxHistory and criticism. 0aRacism in higher educationzUnited States. 0aRacism in motion pictures. 0aResearchxMethodology. 7aHISTORY / Study & Teaching.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2019 Englishz978311061076508iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2019z9783110664232oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE History 2019 Englishz978311061017808iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE History 2019z9783110606195oZDB-23-DEG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUCA Complete eBook-Package 2019z978311065207908iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Complete eBook-Package 2019z978311066763940uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/9780520973190?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520973190423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520973190/original  a978-3-11-061017-8  EBOOK PACKAGE History 2019 Englishb2019  a978-3-11-061076-5  EBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2019 Englishb2019  a978-3-11-065207-9  UCA Complete eBook-Package 2019b2019